<dl id="un2002c"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="un2" href="#un2002">UN2: </a>  <a href="../../FF/unbs/un2all.htm#un2002c"> (VI.D.7) 2(c)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> Summer day St Mary&apos;s Abbey <small>color t.b.a.</small></blockquote> <dd class="well"> <ul class="list-inline" id="un2002c"><li>Ulysses </li><li><a href="../../ulex/l/lexl.htm#un2002c">2021</a> </li><li><a href="../../ulex/l/l86.htm#un2002c">2017</a> </li><li><a href="../../ulex/l/l86.htm#un2002c">1986 (10.408-9)</a> </li><li><a href="../../ulex/l/l22l.htm#un2002c">1922</a> </li><li><ms href="#un2002c">MS Ros-13</ms> </li><li><a name="l12d" href="../udra/u10da.htm#l12d">Usage</a> </li><li><a href="../../ulex/l/l12d.htm#un2002c">Draft: 10.2</a> </li> </ul><mm class="note">Note: Copied to <a name="s12007b" href="s12all.htm#s12007b">Sheet 12.007(b)</a> </mm> <blockquote class="sources">About the beginning of June <font color="green">[1534]</font> a report obtained currency in Ireland, through the machinations of the Ormonde faction, that his father had been summarily executed in the Tower, and that his own death and that of his uncles had been determined upon by his government. Full of indignation at what he considered an act of gross perfidy, he summoned the council to <mark>St. Mary&apos;s Abbey</mark>, whither on <mark>11 June</mark> he rode through the city, accompanied by 140 horsemen with silken fringes on their helmets (whence his sobriquet &lsquo;Silken Thomas&rsquo;), and there, despite the remonstrances of his advisers and the chancellor Cromer, he publicly renounced his allegiance, and formally declared war on the government. <small> <a name="DNBF" href="/udra/udex.htm#DNBF"><cite title="source">Dictionary of National Biography</cite></a> (1889), &ldquo;Thomas Fitzgerald&rdquo;</small></blockquote> </dd></dl>
